The Lex Calpurnia, of Β. c. 67, must have done away with the arrangement, which seems to have been re·embodied in the Lex Julia: it carried the penalty (besides a fine) of perpetual exclusion from the senate and from public office. This Lex was in force at the date of the speech pro Cluentio, but the case to which Cicero refers must have occurred before the Lex Calpurnia was introduced.
